Day 5: Define Segmentation Use Case & Select Image

Chosen Use Case:

Automated Supervision of Cashier Change Transactions in Supermarkets

Problem Statement:

In retail environments like supermarkets, ensuring cashiers provide the correct change is crucial for customer satisfaction and loss prevention. Manual supervision is impractical, and occasional mistakes, whether accidental or intentional, can lead to customer disputes and erode trust. An automated system is needed to monitor cash transactions, specifically the change given back, to detect discrepancies. The core challenge is to accurately identify and count the coins returned to the customer using visual information, often in real-time or near real-time, under potentially variable checkout counter conditions.

Practical Use Case & Aim:

The aim is to develop an automated supervision system that uses computer vision to monitor the coins placed on the counter or tray by a cashier as change. By segmenting and identifying the individual coins from camera footage overlooking the checkout area, the system can calculate the total value of the change given. This calculated value can then be compared against the expected change amount (derived from the point-of-sale system) to flag potential errors. This helps improve cashier accuracy, enhances customer experience by ensuring correct change, and provides a tool for management oversight.

Image Selection:

Selected Image URL (Example):
https://pixabay.com/ (Source: Pixabay License - Free for commercial)

Objectives of the Experiments:

  • To segment the coins from the background using at least two classical image processing methods (e.g., thresholding, watershed).
  • To refine the resulting segmentation masks using morphological operations.
  • To extract each segmented coin as a separate object and count them.
  • To measure key properties (Area, Perimeter, Circularity) for each coin (useful for potential denomination identification).
  • To generate a skeleton for one representative coin object (less relevant for this use case, but kept for technical exploration).
  • To evaluate the effectiveness of the chosen methods for the coin counting aspect of the cashier supervision use case.

import cv2
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

image_path = "./euros.JPG"


def display_image(image, title="Image", cmap=None, figsize=(6, 6)):
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    if cmap:
        # Ensure image is 2D for colormaps
        if len(image.shape) > 2:
            image_display = image[
                :, :, 0
            ]  # Display first channel if multi-channel grayscale
        else:
            image_display = image
        plt.imshow(image_display, cmap=cmap)
    else:
        # OpenCV BGR to Matplotlib RGB
        if len(image.shape) == 3:
            plt.imshow(cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
        else:
            plt.imshow(image, cmap="gray")  # Grayscale
    plt.title(title)
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.show()


try:
    # Read the image from the file path
    source_image_coins = cv2.imread(image_path)

    if source_image_coins is None:
        raise ValueError("Image loading failed.")
    display_image(source_image_coins, title="Source Image: Coins on Dark Surface")

except Exception as e:
    print(f"Error processing image: {e}")
    source_image_coins = None

Day 6: Segment Objects with Classical Methods

Analysis & Parameter Exploration

Two classical image processing methods were implemented for segmenting the coins: Otsu's thresholding and Watershed segmentation. Both are suitable approaches, with Otsu being simpler and effective for high-contrast cases like this, while Watershed is more powerful for separating connected or touching objects. Watershed is generally considered a more advanced classical technique due to its complexity involving marker generation.

Parameter Exploration:

  • Preprocessing (Gaussian Blur): Applied before both methods to reduce noise.

    • Kernel Size: I experimented with different kernel sizes (3x3, 7x7, 11x11). Smaller kernels preserve finer details but retain more noise; larger kernels provide more smoothing but risk blurring object boundaries. The 7x7 size was chosen as a primary balance for this image in the main workflow.

  • Method 1 (Otsu's Thresholding):

    • Threshold Value: Otsu's method automatically determines the threshold. Its performance, however, is influenced by the preceding blur step, as demonstrated by applying Otsu after different blur levels.

  • Method 2 (Watershed Segmentation): This method involves several parameter choices. I specifically experimented with the Sure Foreground Threshold.

    • Sure Foreground Threshold: I tested thresholding the distance transform at different percentages (3%, 5%, 10%, 20%) of its maximum value. Lower values risk merging distinct objects, while higher values might miss objects or oversegment them. The experiment shows how sensitive the final Watershed result is to this parameter. The 10% (0.1) threshold was used for the primary workflow.

# Convert source image to grayscale for thresholding and watershed preparation
gray_coins = cv2.cvtColor(source_image_coins, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
display_image(gray_coins, title="Grayscale Image", cmap="gray")

# --- Parameter Exploration: Gaussian Blur Kernel Size ---
print("\n--- Experiment: Gaussian Blur Kernel Size ---")
kernel_sizes = [(3, 3), (7, 7), (11, 11)]
blurred_images = {}
for k_size in kernel_sizes:
    blurred_img = cv2.GaussianBlur(gray_coins, k_size, 0)
    blurred_images[k_size] = blurred_img
    display_image(
        blurred_img, title=f"Blurred Grayscale (Kernel={k_size})", cmap="gray"
    )

# --- Parameter Exploration: Otsu's Thresholding after different Blurs ---
print("\n--- Experiment: Otsu's Thresholding after Different Blurs ---")
otsu_masks = {}
for k_size in kernel_sizes:
    ret_val, otsu_mask_exp = cv2.threshold(
        blurred_images[k_size], 0, 255, cv2.THRESH_BINARY + cv2.THRESH_OTSU
    )
    otsu_masks[k_size] = otsu_mask_exp
    display_image(
        otsu_mask_exp,
        title=f"Otsu's Mask (after {k_size} Blur) | Thresh={ret_val}",
        cmap="gray",
    )

# --- Main Workflow Segmentation ---
# We'll proceed using the 7x7 blur for the main path
print("\n--- Main Workflow using 7x7 Blur ---")
blurred_coins_main = blurred_images[(7, 7)]
otsu_mask_main = otsu_masks[(7, 7)]
display_image(
    otsu_mask_main,
    title="Method 1: Otsu's Thresholding (Chosen for Main Workflow)",
    cmap="gray",
)

# --- Method 2: Watershed Segmentation ---
# Steps 1-3: Standard preprocessing (using the main 7x7 blurred image)
ret_inv, thresh_inv = cv2.threshold(
    blurred_coins_main, 0, 255, cv2.THRESH_BINARY_INV + cv2.THRESH_OTSU
)
kernel_ws = np.ones((3, 3), np.uint8)
opening_ws = cv2.morphologyEx(thresh_inv, cv2.MORPH_OPEN, kernel_ws, iterations=2)
sure_bg = cv2.dilate(opening_ws, kernel_ws, iterations=3)
dist_transform = cv2.distanceTransform(opening_ws, cv2.DIST_L2, 5)

# --- Parameter Exploration: Watershed Sure Foreground Threshold ---
print("\n--- Experiment: Watershed Sure Foreground Threshold ---")
watershed_results = {}
foreground_thresholds = [0.03, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2]  # Test 3%, 5%, 10%, 20% of max distance

for fg_thresh_factor in foreground_thresholds:
    print(f"\nTesting Watershed Foreground Threshold Factor: {fg_thresh_factor}")
    # Step 4: Sure Foreground Area Calculation
    thresh_value = fg_thresh_factor * dist_transform.max()
    ret_fg, sure_fg_exp = cv2.threshold(dist_transform, thresh_value, 255, 0)
    sure_fg_exp = np.uint8(sure_fg_exp)

    # Steps 5-7: Watershed execution for this threshold
    unknown_exp = cv2.subtract(sure_bg, sure_fg_exp)
    ret_markers_exp, markers_exp = cv2.connectedComponents(sure_fg_exp)
    markers_exp = markers_exp + 1
    markers_exp[unknown_exp == 255] = 0

    # Apply Watershed algorithm - use a copy of source_image_coins
    markers_ws_applied = cv2.watershed(source_image_coins.copy(), markers_exp.copy())

    # Create binary mask from result
    watershed_mask_exp = np.zeros_like(gray_coins, dtype=np.uint8)
    watershed_mask_exp[markers_ws_applied > 1] = 255
    watershed_results[fg_thresh_factor] = watershed_mask_exp

    # Visualize boundaries for this experiment
    watershed_boundaries_vis_exp = source_image_coins.copy()
    watershed_boundaries_vis_exp[markers_ws_applied == -1] = [0, 255, 0]
    display_image(
        watershed_boundaries_vis_exp,
        title=f"Watershed Boundaries (FG Thresh Factor={fg_thresh_factor})",
    )
    display_image(
        watershed_mask_exp,
        title=f"Watershed Mask (FG Thresh Factor={fg_thresh_factor})",
        cmap="gray",
    )

watershed_mask_main = watershed_results[0.1]
print("\n--- Method 2: Watershed Result (using 0.1 FG Threshold Factor) ---")
display_image(
    watershed_mask_main,
    title="Method 2: Watershed Mask (FG Thresh Factor=0.1)",
    cmap="gray",
)
